Onion Price Forecast

1. Introduction

Forecasting prices of staple foods such as cabbage and potatoes is important because of its direct impact on a countrys economy and society. Nepal, in this case, is a country with a large agricultural sector that contributes to a large part of the countrys GDP. The price of staple foods affects not only farmers incomes, but also the economy of the country. These Nepalese staple food prices are also important to forecast as they indicate consumer purchasing power and the general rate of inflation in the country. By predicting these prices one can promote informed decisions, reduce risks and promote economic stability. Forecasting prices for staple foods is and will always be important.

Main goal: accurately forecast the prices of key vegetables in Nepal over a specific time horizon.

Dataset: The data set consists of vegetables in Nepal, where each vegetable represents a time series. The data is of a daily-nature, but it has been transformed into monthly data for the sake of this analysis and forecasting project.

1.1 Data Preparation

Loading the data sets: fruits and vegetables prices in Nepal, as well as the Consumer Price Index (CPI) for Nepal. The fruits and vegetables table contains the average price for vegetables and fruits on a given day. For the time series analysis this will be aggregated to the month level by taking the average of the average daily prices in a particular month.

The generated tsibble looks like this.

# Loading Datasets.
veggies <- read_csv("../data_sources/kalimati_tarkari_dataset.csv", 
                    col_types = cols(Date = col_date(format = "%Y-%m-%d")))

suppressWarnings({
  cpi <- read_excel("../data_sources/Nepal CPI Trading Economics.xlsx", 
                    col_types = c("date", "numeric"))
})

cpi <- cpi |>
  filter(Date >= '2013-08-01 00:00:00')

# tidy up cpi
base_index <- cpi$CPI[1]
cpi <- cpi |>
  mutate(Date = yearmonth(cpi$Date),
         CPI = CPI/base_index) |>
  select(c(Date, CPI))

suppressMessages({
  veggies <- veggies %>%
    filter(Unit == "Kg") %>%
    filter(Commodity %in% c("Tomato Big(Nepali)", "Potato Red",
                            "Onion Dry (Indian)", "Carrot(Local)",
                            "Cabbage(Local)")) %>%
    mutate(Date = yearmonth(Date)) %>%
    select(Commodity, Date, Average) %>%
    group_by(Date, Commodity) %>%
    summarize(Average = mean(Average)) %>%
    ungroup()
})

veggies_ts <- veggies |>
  as_tsibble(key = Commodity,
             index = Date)

head(veggies_ts, 5)

Forecasting for the Onion

Looking at the initial plot of the Onion there is a strong cyclic behavior, this is not uncommon in agriculture because most veggies is sensitive to weather conditions, the price usually depends on harvesting and so called crop-rotations where farmers swap the veggie they grow for soil fertility and so on. Agriculture is generally speaking pretty sensitive so a lot of outside factors. We can see a high increase/spike at the end of every second year and a dip/decrease at the beginning of every second year. Since this is with a 2 year interval it makes the cyclic behavior very apparent.Between this increase and decrease the price is relatively stable with a possible seasonality. When it comes to the trend its not something that is very apparent for the naked eye, but ofc, the prices would naturally increase over time - just like everything else.

Onion <- veggies_ts %>% 
  filter(Commodity == "Onion Dry (Indian)")

Onion %>% 
  autoplot(Average) +
  labs(y="Nepalese Rupee",
       title="Average Price of Onion") +
  theme_bw()

# Subseries In the subseries plot below we can see that the most expensive month is December and that the price increases from August up until December and drops in January, then stabilizes over the summer.

Onion %>% 
  gg_subseries(Average) +
  labs(y="Nepalese Rupee",
       title="Average Price Onion") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank())

# Autocorrelation function (ACF) Looking at the ACF we can first of all we can see that we have 6 significant lags. We can also see that the first two lags are the most significant. We also have two significant lags that are seasonal (lag 6 is very questionable because it is barely visible) but lag 24 is significant. lag 24 confirms our suspicions on the cyclic behaviour since it indicates that the patterns repeats every two years, just as we have seen in previous plots, so we have some sort of long-term pattern that once again, can be due to harvesting or similar agriculture activities.

Onion %>% 
  ACF(Average, lag_max = 24) %>%  
  autoplot() +
  labs(title="Autocorrelation - Onion") +
  theme_bw()

# Tranformations Looking at previous plots it is not suggested that a mathematical transformation (log) would be needed because there is no multiplicative pattern or clear positive trend or any of that sort.One transformation that we do deem necessary is related to the price and the inflation. So the transformation performed was to adjust the onion prices for inflation (with the CPI), this is mainly to show the real purchasing power and make comparison over time more accurate.

When it comes to the box-cox transformation, which is mainly for normalizing skewed data and remove heteroskedasticity, we double check by plotting the before and after (of the box-cox) to verify if it is needed or not. The box-cox transformation did account for some variance, hence we decided to apply it.

Onion_constant_prices <- Onion |>
  inner_join(cpi, by = join_by(Date)) |>
  mutate(Average_constant_prices = Average / CPI) |>
  select(Date, Commodity, Average_constant_prices)
head(Onion_constant_prices, 5)

# Decomposition models We choose various decomposition models for the Onion to evaluate which one is the best. When it comes to the STL2 model we set window 72 in the trend to catch any trend in the span of our data, and season window to 24 to match our seasonal lag at 24 (cyclic behavior). In the plot below we can see that the best suited decomposition model is the X13 (Arima Seats) because it captures the trend and the seasonality/cyclic pattern the best out of all models.

but looking at the residuals (that does not resemble white noise) we cans see that this model was not acceptable, even if it was the best, this suggest that we should keep looking for a better model.

Onion_constant_prices %>%
  model(STL1 = STL(Average_constant_prices),
        STL2 = STL(Average_constant_prices ~ trend(window = 72 ) + season(window = 24), robust = TRUE),
        fixed = STL(Average_constant_prices ~ season(window = "periodic"), robust = TRUE),
        x13 = X_13ARIMA_SEATS(Average_constant_prices),
        seats = X_13ARIMA_SEATS(Average_constant_prices ~ seats()))%>%
  components() -> dcmpOnion

dcmpOnion %>% as_tsibble() %>% autoplot(trend)

dcmpOnion %>% as_tsibble() %>% autoplot(season_adjust)

autoplot(dcmpOnion)

Onion_X13 <- Onion_constant_prices %>%
  model(RW(Average_constant_prices ~ drift()))

Onion_X13 %>% gg_tsresiduals()

## 4. The forecasters toolbox Looking at models that might suit the Onion data for forecasting we are evaluating the naive, seasonal naive, drift and mean model. we have a total of 94 rows, so we can use 26 for training and leave the rest.The best model here (which has the lowest RMSE) is the drift model, but it not necessarily that much better than the Arima_x13. The residuals are still not representing white noise.

num_rows <- nrow(Onion_constant_prices)
print(num_rows)
## [1] 94
train_onion <- Onion_constant_prices %>% slice(1:(n() - 60))

fit_onion <- train_onion %>%
  model(
    Naive = NAIVE(Average_constant_prices),
    Seasonal_Naive = SNAIVE(Average_constant_prices),
    Drift = RW(Average_constant_prices ~ drift()),
    Mean = MEAN(Average_constant_prices)
  )

fit_onion %>% accuracy() %>% arrange(RMSE)

## 5. Exponential smoothing

Looking at the Onion ACF we can see that it is stationary. Since we already have evaluated the data and we know that we have both seasonality and cyclic behavior we would suggest that we have a multiplicative error and seasonality, to capture all of these different changes in the onion price over time, also because the onion increase and decrease a lot over time and showcase variation. Since the trend is not very apparent we can use a N on the trend. the model would hence me a MNM-model.The best model for the onion out of the models below is the MNM-model, that is also the model that was chosen when performing ETS. So far this is the best model we have seen so far, even if we still have significant lags in the residuals (ACF).

Onion_ExponentialSmoothing <- Onion_constant_prices %>% 
  model(MNM = ETS(Average_constant_prices ~ error("M") + trend("N") + season("M")),
        holt = ETS(Average_constant_prices ~ error("A") + trend("A") + season("N")),
        ses = ETS(Average_constant_prices ~ error("A") + trend("N") + season("N")),
        ETS = ETS(Average_constant_prices))

report(Onion_ExponentialSmoothing)

Arima

Our data is already stationary so we do not need to do any difference! Looking at our the ACF and PACF we see that we have two significant lags in the PACF (lag 1 and 2) indicating that an AR model of order 2 could be suitable. In the ACF we have also the first two lags as significant, but we also have two more barely significant lags, hence we choose to try the AR2 model which in this context makes the most sense, because of its simplicity.

We also included the auto-model to find the best fit, which was the better choice, but not too much better than the model we choice. But it has a slightly lower (almost insignificantly lower) BIC, AIC and AICc. The auto model suggest that we should have a seasonal component (12 months/yearly) and a SAR model as Arima(2,0,0)(0,0,2)[12]

Both of these models have residuals that resemble white noise and hence, we have finally found a good forecasting model for the onion!

Onion_constant_prices %>% gg_tsdisplay((Average_constant_prices), plot_type = "partial")

Onion_fit <- Onion_constant_prices %>% 
  model(Arima2 = ARIMA(Average_constant_prices ~ pdq(2,0,0)),
    auto = ARIMA(Average_constant_prices, stepwise = FALSE, approx = FALSE))

glance(Onion_fit) %>% 
         arrange(AICc) %>% 
         select(.model:BIC)
## # A tibble: 2  6
##   .model sigma2 log_lik   AIC  AICc   BIC

## 2 Arima2  106.    -352.  712.  713.  722.
Onion_fit %>% 
  select(Arima2) %>%
